Expected vs. observed (from docs/new_sources_plan.md):
  human_rights:          Expected moderate positive (0.3-0.6), observed -0.185
  arms_control:          Expected moderate positive (0.3-0.5), observed -0.480
  intellectual_property: Expected low (0.0-0.3), observed +0.479

Interpretation notes:
  - Sign conventions matter: The expected correlations in the plan assumed
    positive ideal points would align with the positive direction of UNGA
    voting. However, the dynIRT sign is determined by anchor placement and
    PCA orientation, not by a priori substantive direction.

  - HUMAN RIGHTS: Positive IP = low ratification (STP, SOM, FJI); negative
    IP = high ratification (BOL, ESP, ECU). The weak negative UNGA correlation
    (-0.185) suggests HR treaty ratification is only loosely related to UNGA
    voting alignment. This is substantively plausible — HR ratification is
    driven by domestic legal/constitutional factors distinct from geopolitical
    UNGA bloc voting.

  - ARMS CONTROL: Positive IP = pro-disarmament anchored by NZL; negative =
    anti-disarmament anchored by ISR. The strong negative UNGA correlation
    (-0.48) indicates that countries our model codes as pro-disarmament tend
    to have different UNGA alignment than what the UNGA ideal point scale
    captures. This is consistent with the Phase 3 observation that IRN/PAK/SAU
    cluster near the pro-disarmament end — these are countries that support
    multilateral disarmament frameworks but vote differently from Western
    democracies at UNGA.

  - INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY: Positive IP = high WIPO engagement (MDA, ROU, SVK);
    negative = low engagement (ZMB, VNM, TZA). The moderate positive UNGA
    correlation (+0.48) was stronger than expected. WIPO engagement appears to
    track with broader multilateral engagement patterns that also drive UNGA
    voting similarity.

